Homework 2: Matrices Solutions

Problem 1: Matrix-Description Matching

Match the descriptions a)-f) with matrices 1)-6):

Descriptions:

  1. Rotation by \(70Â°\)
  2. Not changing anything
  3. Flipping around the \(x\)-axis
  4. Stretching out \(5\) times in \(y\)-direction
  5. Sending all vectors onto the line \(y=6x\)
  6. Sending all vectors onto the line \(y=6x+1\)

Matrices:

  1. \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&5 \end{bmatrix}\)
  2. Such matrix does not exist
  3. \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&1 \end{bmatrix}\)
  4. \(\begin{bmatrix} 0.342 & -0.939\\ 0.939& 0.342 \end{bmatrix}\)
  5. \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&-1 \end{bmatrix}\)
  6. \(\begin{bmatrix} 3&-1\\18&-6 \end{bmatrix}\)

Hint: Compute the determinants.

Solutions

Letâs analyze each matrix and compute determinants:

Matrix 1: \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&5 \end{bmatrix}\) - \(\det = 5\) â (stretches \(y\) by 5)

Matrix 2: No matrix exists for affine transformations (translations)

Matrix 3: \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&1 \end{bmatrix}\) - \(\det = 1\) â (identity matrix)

Matrix 4: \(\begin{bmatrix} 0.342 & -0.939\\ 0.939& 0.342 \end{bmatrix}\) - \(\det = 0.342^2 + 0.939^2 \approx 1\) â (rotation matrix)

Matrix 5: \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0\\0&-1 \end{bmatrix}\) - \(\det = -1\) â (reflection across \(x\)-axis)

Matrix 6: \(\begin{bmatrix} 3&-1\\18&-6 \end{bmatrix}\) - \(\det = 3(-6) - (-1)(18) = 0\) â (projects onto line)

Matching:

    1. Rotation by \(70Â°\) â 4 (Note: \(\cos(70Â°) \approx 0.342\), \(\sin(70Â°) \approx 0.939\))
    1. Not changing anything â 3 (Identity matrix)
    1. Flipping around \(x\)-axis â 5 (Changes \(y\) to \(-y\))
    1. Stretching \(5\) times in \(y\)-direction â 1 (Scales \(y\)-coordinate by 5)
    1. Sending all vectors onto line \(y=6x\) â 6 (Determinant = 0, projects onto line)
    1. Sending all vectors onto line \(y=6x+1\) â 2 (Linear transformations canât translate)

Problem 2: Determinants

What is the determinant of the matrix which:

  1. Rotates everything by \(14Â°\) and stretches \(1.5\) times in the \(x\)-direction
  2. Does the inverse of a)
  3. Sends \([1 \quad 0]\) to \([2 \quad 4]\) and \([0 \quad 1]\) to \([-1 \quad 0]\)
  4. Has the form \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 3 \\ 2 &1 \end{bmatrix}\)
  5. Has the form \(\begin{bmatrix} 8&3&5\\1&4&2\\-4&0&4 \end{bmatrix}\)
  6. Is the matrix of e) raised to the power \(3\)

Solutions

  1. Rotation + scaling matrix: Rotation preserves area (\(\det = 1\)), scaling by \(1.5\) in \(x\)-direction multiplies area by \(1.5\). \(\det = 1.5\)

  2. Inverse matrix: \(\det(A^{-1}) = \frac{1}{\det(A)} = \frac{1}{1.5} = \frac{2}{3}\)

  3. Matrix from column vectors: \(A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ 4 & 0 \end{bmatrix}\) \(\det(A) = 2(0) - (-1)(4) = 4\)

  4. Direct calculation: \(\det = 2(1) - 3(2) = 2 - 6 = -4\)

  5. 3Ã3 determinant: Using cofactor expansion along the second row: \(\det = -1 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 3&5\\0&4 \end{vmatrix} + 4 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 8&5\\-4&4 \end{vmatrix} - 2 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 8&3\\-4&0 \end{vmatrix}\) \(= -1(12) + 4(32 + 20) - 2(0 + 12) = -12 + 208 - 24 = 172\)

  6. Power property: \(\det(A^3) = (\det(A))^3 = 172^3 = 5,088,448\)

Problem 3: Missing Matrix Entries

Fill in the missing entries of \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & * \\ -1 & * \end{bmatrix}\) if it:

  1. Stretches \([0 \quad 1]\) by \(2\) times
  2. Has trace \(2\) and determinant \(3\)
  3. Has eigenvalues \(1\) and \(5\)

Solutions

ð¹ Video Solution in Armenian

  1. Stretching \([0 \quad 1]\) by 2: \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & * \\ -1 & * \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = 2\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}\)

    This gives us: \(\begin{bmatrix} * \\ * \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}\)

    Therefore: \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}\)

  2. Trace = 2, determinant = 3: Let the matrix be \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & a \\ -1 & b \end{bmatrix}\)

    • Trace: \(2 + b = 2 \Rightarrow b = 0\)
    • Determinant: \(2b - a(-1) = 3 \Rightarrow a = -3\)

    Therefore: \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & -3 \\ -1 & 0 \end{bmatrix}\)

  3. Eigenvalues 1 and 5: For eigenvalues \(\lambda_1 = 1\) and \(\lambda_2 = 5\):

    • Trace = \(\lambda_1 + \lambda_2 = 6\)
    • Determinant = \(\lambda_1 \cdot \lambda_2 = 5\)

    Let the matrix be \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & a \\ -1 & b \end{bmatrix}\)

    • \(2 + b = 6 \Rightarrow b = 4\)
    • \(2(4) - a(-1) = 5 \Rightarrow 8 + a = 5 \Rightarrow a = -3\)

    Therefore: \(\begin{bmatrix} 2 & -3 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}\)

Problem 4: Subspace Dimensions

A subspace of which dimension (at most) can you construct with the vectors:

  1. \(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}6\\1\\5\end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix} 2\\3\\2 \end{bmatrix}\)

  2. \(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}6\\2\end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix} 1\\3 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_3=\begin{bmatrix} 5\\2 \end{bmatrix}\)

  3. \(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}4\\1\\2\end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix} -4\\2\\-1 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_3=\begin{bmatrix} 8\\-1\\7 \end{bmatrix}\)

  4. \(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}3\\-2\\1\end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix} 6\\-4\\4 \end{bmatrix}\)

Solutions

The dimension equals the number of linearly independent vectors (rank of the matrix).

  1. Two vectors in \(\mathbb{R}^3\): Check if linearly independent: \(\mathbf{v}_1\) and \(\mathbf{v}_2\) are not scalar multiples. Dimension: 2 (span a plane in \(\mathbb{R}^3\))

  2. Three vectors in \(\mathbb{R}^2\): At most 2 vectors can be linearly independent in \(\mathbb{R}^2\). Check: \(\det\begin{bmatrix} 6&1\\2&3 \end{bmatrix} = 18-2 = 16 \neq 0\) Dimension: 2 (any two non-collinear vectors span \(\mathbb{R}^2\))

  3. Three vectors in \(\mathbb{R}^3\): Form matrix: \(\begin{bmatrix} 4&-4&8\\1&2&-1\\2&-1&7 \end{bmatrix}\)

    Computing determinant: \(\det = 4(14-1) - (-4)(7+2) + 8(-1-4) = 4(13) + 4(9) + 8(-5) = 52 + 36 - 40 = 48 \neq 0\) Dimension: 3 (linearly independent)

  4. Two vectors in \(\mathbb{R}^3\): Check if \(\mathbf{v}_2 = k\mathbf{v}_1\): \(\frac{6}{3} = 2\), \(\frac{-4}{-2} = 2\), but \(\frac{4}{1} = 4 \neq 2\) Dimension: 2 (linearly independent, span a plane)

Problem 5: Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors

Find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the following matrices:

  1. \(A=\begin{bmatrix} 1&2\\0&1\end{bmatrix}\)
  2. \(B=\begin{bmatrix} 2&1\\1&2 \end{bmatrix}\)
  3. \(C=\begin{bmatrix} 8 & 1 \\ 8 & 1 \end{bmatrix}\)
  4. \(D=\begin{bmatrix} -1&0&0\\0&1&0\\0&0&3 \end{bmatrix}\)

You may use any technique but try to think visually.

Solutions

  1. Matrix \(A=\begin{bmatrix} 1&2\\0&1\end{bmatrix}\) (Upper triangular):

    Characteristic polynomial: \(\det(A-\lambda I) = (1-\lambda)^2 = 0\) Eigenvalue: \(\lambda = 1\) (repeated)

    For \(\lambda = 1\): \((A-I)\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) \(\begin{bmatrix} 0&2\\0&0 \end{bmatrix}\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) Eigenvector: \(\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\0 \end{bmatrix}\) (geometric multiplicity = 1)

  2. Matrix \(B=\begin{bmatrix} 2&1\\1&2 \end{bmatrix}\) (Symmetric):

    Characteristic polynomial: \(\det(B-\lambda I) = (2-\lambda)^2 - 1 = \lambda^2 - 4\lambda + 3 = (\lambda-1)(\lambda-3)\) Eigenvalues: \(\lambda_1 = 1\), \(\lambda_2 = 3\)

    For \(\lambda_1 = 1\): \(\begin{bmatrix} 1&1\\1&1 \end{bmatrix}\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) â \(\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\-1 \end{bmatrix}\) For \(\lambda_2 = 3\): \(\begin{bmatrix} -1&1\\1&-1 \end{bmatrix}\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) â \(\mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\1 \end{bmatrix}\)

  3. Matrix \(C=\begin{bmatrix} 8 & 1 \\ 8 & 1 \end{bmatrix}\) (Rank-deficient):

    Notice: \(\det(C) = 8(1) - 1(8) = 0\), so \(\lambda = 0\) is an eigenvalue. Trace = \(8 + 1 = 9\), so other eigenvalue is \(9\). Eigenvalues: \(\lambda_1 = 0\), \(\lambda_2 = 9\)

    For \(\lambda_1 = 0\): \(C\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) â \(\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\-8 \end{bmatrix}\) For \(\lambda_2 = 9\): \((C-9I)\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}\) â \(\mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\8 \end{bmatrix}\)

  4. Matrix \(D=\begin{bmatrix} -1&0&0\\0&1&0\\0&0&3 \end{bmatrix}\) (Diagonal):

    For diagonal matrices, eigenvalues are the diagonal entries: Eigenvalues: \(\lambda_1 = -1\), \(\lambda_2 = 1\), \(\lambda_3 = 3\) Eigenvectors: \(\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\0\\0 \end{bmatrix}\), \(\mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\1\\0 \end{bmatrix}\), \(\mathbf{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\0\\1 \end{bmatrix}\)

Visual interpretation: Eigenvectors show directions that are only scaled (not rotated) by the matrix transformation.

Problem 6: Ellipse Area

If you take the unit circle \(x^2+y^2=1\) and stretch it out \(2\) times along the \(x\)-axis, you will get an ellipse. What is its area equal to?

(Additional:) Can you generalize the result to derive a formula for the area of ellipse?

Solutions

Main Problem: The transformation matrix is \(T = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}\) (stretch by 2 in \(x\)-direction).

The determinant is \(\det(T) = 2 \cdot 1 = 2\).

Since linear transformations scale areas by the absolute value of the determinant: - Original area (unit circle): \(\pi\) - New area (ellipse): \(|\det(T)| \cdot \pi = 2\pi\)

Generalization: For an ellipse with semi-axes \(a\) and \(b\), the transformation from unit circle is: \[T = \begin{bmatrix} a & 0 \\ 0 & b \end{bmatrix}\]

General ellipse area formula: \(\text{Area} = \pi ab\)

Verification: - Unit circle: \(a = b = 1 \Rightarrow \text{Area} = \pi\) - Our problem: \(a = 2, b = 1 \Rightarrow \text{Area} = 2\pi\) â

This beautiful result shows how determinants give us area scaling factors for linear transformations!

Problem 7: Inverse Problems

It is known that the matrix \(A=\begin{bmatrix} 4 & -8 \\ 1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}\) sends a certain vector \(\mathbf{v}\) to:

  1. \(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\2 \end{bmatrix}\)
  2. \(\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}\)

Can you find the vector \(\mathbf{v}\)?

Solutions

We need to solve \(A\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{b}\) for \(\mathbf{v}\), which means \(\mathbf{v} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}\).

First, find \(A^{-1}\): \[A = \begin{bmatrix} 4 & -8 \\ 1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}\] \[\det(A) = 4(2) - (-8)(1) = 8 + 8 = 16\] \[A^{-1} = \frac{1}{16}\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 8 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/8 & 1/2 \\ -1/16 & 1/4 \end{bmatrix}\]

  1. For \(\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}\): \[\mathbf{v} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/8 & 1/2 \\ -1/16 & 1/4 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/8 + 1 \\ -1/16 + 1/2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 9/8 \\ 7/16 \end{bmatrix}\]

  2. For \(\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}\): \[\mathbf{v} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/8 & 1/2 \\ -1/16 & 1/4 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3/8 + 2 \\ -3/16 + 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 19/8 \\ 13/16 \end{bmatrix}\]

Verification for a): \(A\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 & -8 \\ 1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 9/8 \\ 7/16 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 9/2 - 7/2 \\ 9/8 + 7/8 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}\) â

Problem 8: Diagonal Matrix Properties (Additional)

Consider the \(5 \times 5\) matrix: \[A=\begin{bmatrix} a_1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & a_2 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & a_3 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & a_4 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & a_5 \end{bmatrix}\]

where \(a_1, \dots, a_5\) are positive numbers.

  1. What is the standard basis of \(\mathbb{R}^5\)?
  2. Where does \(A\) send the standard basis vectors?
  3. What is the determinant of \(A\)?
  4. What are the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of \(A\)?

Solutions

  1. Standard basis of \(\mathbb{R}^5\): \[\mathbf{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\0\\0\\0\\0 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{e}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\1\\0\\0\\0 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{e}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\0\\1\\0\\0 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{e}_4 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\0\\0\\1\\0 \end{bmatrix}, \mathbf{e}_5 = \begin{bmatrix} 0\\0\\0\\0\\1 \end{bmatrix}\]

  2. Where \(A\) sends the basis vectors: \[A\mathbf{e}_1 = a_1\mathbf{e}_1, \quad A\mathbf{e}_2 = a_2\mathbf{e}_2, \quad A\mathbf{e}_3 = a_3\mathbf{e}_3, \quad A\mathbf{e}_4 = a_4\mathbf{e}_4, \quad A\mathbf{e}_5 = a_5\mathbf{e}_5\]

    Each basis vector is scaled by its corresponding diagonal entry.

  3. Determinant: For diagonal matrices, the determinant is the product of diagonal entries: \[\det(A) = a_1 \cdot a_2 \cdot a_3 \cdot a_4 \cdot a_5\]

  4. Eigenvalues and eigenvectors: From part (b), we see that each \(\mathbf{e}_i\) is an eigenvector with eigenvalue \(a_i\):

    • Eigenvalues: \(\lambda_1 = a_1, \lambda_2 = a_2, \lambda_3 = a_3, \lambda_4 = a_4, \lambda_5 = a_5\)
    • Eigenvectors: \(\mathbf{v}_1 = \mathbf{e}_1, \mathbf{v}_2 = \mathbf{e}_2, \mathbf{v}_3 = \mathbf{e}_3, \mathbf{v}_4 = \mathbf{e}_4, \mathbf{v}_5 = \mathbf{e}_5\)

Key insight: Diagonal matrices are the simplest linear transformationsâthey just scale each coordinate independently!
